<div class="de1">&gt;You‚Äôd take the buses, but none of the routes went to that part of town.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It became a habit for you to trek to her apartment with an extra set of clothes and crash on her couch for the night.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Eventually, you settled into a routine, go to work at the shop, head to her place, sleep, then head home after work in the morning.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Rinse, repeat.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It became enough of a routine, that you left some toiletries over at her place.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Mara herself didn‚Äôt seem the mind the slow invasion of her home, and she often texted you when you were at worked about how lonely she was without you.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The days themselves bled together as your routine settled.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Days.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Weeks.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Eventually Months.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It was a kind of blur to you, it sped by so quickly.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Time really did have a habit of slipping away when you were having fun, and you had fun every day with Mara.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Sometimes you didn‚Äôt even work, you just hung out, watching movies on the sofa, making a new dish together, all sorts of things. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It was an odd homely life, that you couldn‚Äôt help but admit you loved.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You oft found yourself thinking of the little shark girl when you were at work, with her bright blue eyes, and her mop of perpetually messy hair.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And that smile‚Ä¶ oh that smile. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You worked your hardest just so you could see that smile when she read your work.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It was rewarding in its own right.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Mara herself had these little ticks, that amused you.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;When she read anything, she‚Äôd whisper it under her breath, with emphases and accents, as if she was reading to a group of children.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;She would sing recipes when she cooked (Add half a cup of milk~).</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Her particular way of organizing the dishwasher, with all the utensils organized by type and material. (Yes, Anon, plastic forks and metal forks are /completely/ different.)</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;It all blended together, to make a souffl√© of a routine. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Until Mara hit a patch of writers block thicker than a bowl of oatmeal.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt; ‚ÄúUGH!‚Äù Mara groaned, spinning in her chair. ‚ÄúI‚Äôve been sitting here for hours and I‚Äôve not thought of anything! All I‚Äôve written down is ‚ÄòTHE‚Äô in really fancy letters!‚Äù</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The chair had a squealy wheel. </div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;Though to tolerated it for the most part, the fact that the little shark wouldn‚Äôt stop spinning on her chair was starting to grate on your nerves.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;You had enough, and slamming the desk a little more forcefully than needed, you stood up.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">‚ÄúHow about we go for a walk?‚Äù</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&nbsp;</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;The air was tepid, not unlike the air above a hot stove, but you didn‚Äôt mind.</div></li><li class="li1"><div class="de1">&gt;And since Mara hadn‚Äôt said a wo